comments.textDisplay:
Well, the horror of the original comes in losing a child. A child experiences a percentage of that when losing a pet. So, PS opens up the possibility of correcting that with Pet Sematary so as to ease the pain of a beloved family pet, before they're ready to understand the concept of death. The problem comes when the child buys the farm and dies, and anyone is going to respond to that. But its equally bad when there is a way to get the child back, but not really.

The horror is, a father or mother wanting some semblance of the child back because it's too painful to deal with, but what comes back is horrific. It's not their child. Because the ground is sour.

comments.textDisplay: I am of the reverse opinion. I didn't think the first half was too bogged down by expositions. In fact I thought it moved along way too fast and cut out too much thus sacrificing the connection between the viewers and the characters as there was not enough space for the characters to grow and develop and thus really affecting the logic in the main character's decision. But certain choices by the filmmakers in the first half i felt were good ones as they serve the changes that they made to the movie. The second half however was where everything goes to hell and totally negates every good choices they made in the first half of the movie. Also, for me, a good remake is to add something new or have something new to say that the original missed out or it would be a pointless remake like so many cash grabbing remakes churned out by Hollywood these days. I was hoping for something more because the filmmakers in interviews were saying they delved deeper into the themes in the book in the last half. Sorely disappointed . What they meant by delving deeper was to show the ending that the original movie and the book hinted at (which is more powerful as it was left to the imagination) in all its messy glory. It became a run of the mill horror show. Worst still the supernatural element of the burial ground instead became front and center the main theme of the film when it was supposed to explore the theme of death and its aftermath. Anyone could tell you this is why most Stephen King adaptations ended up failing. When the writers making the adaptation missed the point and made the plot device becomes the plot itself. Also, if anybody who watched the crappy forgettable sequel rushed out by the studio to cash in on the moderate success of the original and starring among others Edward Furlong (shudder!) can see that the filmmakers of this remake was using that as a template for the last half. Improved crap is still crap and it ruined the goodwill of the first half and the whole movie for me as a result.

comments.textDisplay:
Nah, the original Pet Semetary was better, and far less stupid!

*Spoilers*: (I really don't care about spoiling this movie) Ellie dies in the remake instead of Gage! Why? Because, fuck you! Then the movie continues just as the original, just with the roles of Ellie and Gage swaspped. Oh, and Ellie can apparently turn into different people, as she turns into Jud's wife briefly before killing him. Why? Because fuck you! Then at the end, Ellie kills Rachel, buries her in the burial ground, Rachel impales Louis with a weathervane, and resurrects him. They burn down Jud's house, and find Gage in the car where Louis left him to protect him from Ellie, and Louis motions to Gage, and Gage unlocks the car, implying they kill him and resurrect him. Why? BECAUSE FUCK YOU!!

Honestly, I don't understand why Chris plays down these changes as "being overhyped", because they're not.
